I did some tests with rollback and it does work inside a transaction block. [See documentation](https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/1.11/topics/db/transactions/#savepoints-in-sqlite)

So I made this decorator that actually works pretty well.
```
def safe_migration(func):
    @transaction.atomic
    def func_wrapper(*args, **kwargs):
        sp = savepoint()
        try:
            func(*args, **kwargs)
        except:
            raise
        finally:
            savepoint_rollback(sp)
    return func_wrapper
```

When I decorate my test function with it the issue in the `tearDown` does not occur.

@hongjic The inferencing in distributed mode is just provided as an example.  Generally speaking, it shouldn't be necessary unless your model size exceeds the memory of a single box (i.e. one or more PS nodes are required).  Otherwise, you could:
1. write a single-node version of inferencing and just use the data parallelism capabilities of Spark to inference.  This is useful for batch processing of large datasets.
2. export the model via saved_model_builder and inference via [TF-Serving](https://www.tensorflow.org/serving/serving_basic).  This is useful for smaller datasets and/or inferencing at serving time.

