Hi Håkon,

I'm glad to hear you're trying out NEMO! I'll try to answer your questions best I can. Your description has already given me some good information for improvements to NEMO.

It looks like you are successfully running NEMO. There are some things you may need to do in order to access it. To answer your questions first:

> Am I to leave `django_secret_key.txt` empty?

In your `settings.py` file, I see you have a value set for `SECRET_KEY`, so you will **not** need a `django_secret_key.txt` file. Please note that by posting it on GitHub, it is no longer secret. If you plan to use NEMO in production, I highly recommend you change your secret key. You can generate a new one on the command line using `nemo generate_secret_key`.

> Is the settings file referred to while calling Docker, `/home/user/settings.py` the same as created locally in the `/nemo` dir as per _Development & test settings.py_, which in my case is `/home/<username>/nemo/settings.py`?

I think the answer is yes. You have to provide the `settings.py` file to the Docker container... it does not come packaged with one. So, since your `docker run ...` output is normal (and successfully running NEMO), it appears it's seeing your `settings.py` file correctly.

> Do I need to download the online repo and point to it somehow for NEMO to work with Docker locally?

I don't think I understand the question, because I'm not sure what you mean by "online repo". The Docker image is downloaded from Docker Hub, using the `docker run` command. However, everything else (such as `settings.py`) should be created by you.

---

Some other things you may need to do in order to access NEMO:

Several people have told me they have trouble getting NEMO to authenticate properly against an LDAP server. Any LDAP authentication errors are output as exceptions in NEMO, and the exceptions can be logged to a file. So, you can see the exact issue if logging is configured in `settings.py`. Below is an example logging configuration file that is recommended for production settings. You can open the “django error.log” to see the exception.

```
LOGGING = {
     'version': 1,
     'disable_existing_loggers': False,
     'handlers': {
           'mail_admins': {
                'level': 'INFO',
                'class': 'django.utils.log.AdminEmailHandler'
           },
           'error_file': {
                'level': 'WARNING',
                'class': 'logging.FileHandler',
                'filename': '/home/nemo/logs/django_error.log'
           },
           'security_file': {
                'level': 'INFO',
                'class': 'logging.FileHandler',
                'filename': '/home/nemo/logs/django_security.log'
           },
     },
     'loggers': {
           'django.request': {
                'handlers': ['mail_admins', 'error_file'],
                'level': 'WARNING',
                'propagate': True,
           },
           'django.security': {
                'handlers': ['mail_admins', 'security_file'],
                'level': 'WARNING',
                'propagate': True,
           },
     }
}
```

There is a portion of the documentation that I'm still working on... you'll need to add an initial super user to the NEMO database. You'll have to open a terminal in the running Docker container, and issue the command `python manage.py createsuperuser`. Enter the user information (such as first name, last name, email, as normal. When you're prompted for a password, it doesn't matter what you enter because passwords aren't stored in NEMO's database. The user you create in the NEMO database will have to match up with an account that can be authenticated against in the LDAP server.

Diagnosing LDAP authentication issues in NEMO is particularly difficult (simply because authentication is tough to get right). This has prompted me to make this easier and add authentication diagnostic tools directly into NEMO. I plan to add these to the “nemo” executable that comes with the Python package, so you’ll be able to do this on the command line: `nemo query_public_key` and `nemo test_ldap_authentication`. This feature will be available in version 1.1.0, planned to release by February 6th.

